node.text:
As an overly analytical and rational human I constantly need to remind myself to get out of my head and into my body and soul. I always love to sit and really think about @dr.marielbuque ‘s weekly question : “How is your soul today?”

This tea time is full of coziness and soulful connections. @dr.marielbuque and myself talk about grounding work, connecting with your ancestors, intergenerational healing, and tuning inward for the wisdom of those small acts love and kindness. Your challenge, should you choose to accept it: Set a timer for 5 minutes out of your day to connect with yourself through the senses. Watch the whole video for an in-depth explanation. 

This is the last episode of February’s therapeutic tea series! I’ll be taking some time off to finish launching my course: Breaking the Cycle of Self-Betrayal! Head over to the link in BIO for all the amazing details that I will be pouring in the world (as Mariel would say 😍)!

node.title: Honoring Your Soul and Spirit with @dr.marielbuque

If you’ve ever thought or said to yourself “I’m not actually hungry, I’m thirsty” - bypassing your body’s cues and dishonoring its needs...this one is for you! 

Join @your.latina.nutritionist and myself as we talk about the role of culture in our nutrition and mental nourishment, ditching the diet rules and mentality, using your hunger as information, getting curious with your cravings, restrictions, and smashing all the shame that’s attached to it!

If you’re looking to re-connect with yourself and end the cycle of betrayal and find peace within your body, the doors to my masterclass: Breaking the Cycle of Self-Betrayal are open! Head over to the link in Bio! 

Books referenced in chat: @chr1styharrison - Anti-Diet + Sabrina Strings-Fearing the Black Body.

node.title: Ditching the Diet + Honoring your Body with @your.latina.nutritionist

This morning’s tea was so on point! I had the absolute honor of being joined by @nedratawwab to discuss her new book, Set Boundaries, Find Peace: A Guide to Reclaiming Yourself, out March 16th. 

We often talk about this elusive quest for self-love...for me, it starts with self-respect, self-honor, self-commitment, and none of that can be possible without boundaries.

Join @nedratawwab and myself as we discuss:

-resentment, anger, and the toll lack of boundaries takes on our bodies
-family rules, dynamics and the ways we betray ourselves 
-the 6 types of boundaries you need in your life
-the concept of little b and Big B boundary violations 
-ways we can start to set and also not take other’s boundaries so personally

AND so much more-you do NOT want to miss this tea time.

Don’t forget to pre-order Nedra’s book, head over to her link in bio, it is a golden nugget of pure goodness! ❤️

We are not looking to fit in, we are looking to belong. 

Loved this tea with @browngirltherapy on the intersection between self-betrayal and our need to belong. As the children of immigrants (Sahaj) and an immigrant myself, we discussed our personal experiences with shame and the parts we felt the need to hide or silence in order to fit in. From @brenebrown’s book The Gifts of Imperfection we explore how what we are actually seeking is to connect authentically and belong to communities where we are allowed to be our whole self. Sahaj offers an amazing challenge to us all-watch the video until the end for her beautiful message and words.

Are you struggling with self-betrayal? The doors to my 6-week LIVE course on unlocking self-betrayal will be opening this week! Those on the waitlist get access before everyone else and a special discount. Get your name on the list, limited spots available. Link in bio!

I’m also soooo excited to announce that the doors to my 6-week LIVE course on unlocking self-betrayal will be opening soon! Get your name on the waitlist, limited spots available. If you like quizzes I’ve got you covered and even a free ebook. Link in bio!

We showed up for the tea-the authentic, imperfect and vulnerable versions of ourselves! node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Maria Sosa, MS, MFT, Therapist in Miami, Florida. May be an image of text that says '@holisticallygrace Sometimes, it's not cycles of toxic conflict criticism. Sometimes it's: .little interest in each other's life .loss of shared future plans, dreams unaffectionate physical contact (if any) .separate, parallel living •lack of humor, laughter, joy .unacknowledged, underlying tension .an "everything is fine" mentality-when it isn't •lack of vulnerability, sharing fears, intimacy .feeling like distant roommates'.

node.text:
Sometimes, relationship breakdown doesn’t look like the high levels of negativity found in critical, defensive and contemptuous behaviors but rather the absence of positive affect found in emotional disengagement.

While anger and conflict are rare, there is an underlying and unspoken tension below the surface. In this stage of the relationship, externally “everything is fine” and yet there is a lack of joy, fun, humor and emotional connection. Partners stop experiencing themselves as friends and have becomes distant roommates living parallel lives.

The foundation of healthy and happy relationships is friendship. To reconnect, it’s important to build what @gottmaninstitute calls Love Maps-kinda like a map to your partner’s heart. Check out the Gottman Card Decks App-free for both apple and android to find out more.

Does this look familiar? Share 👇

Photo by Maria Sosa, MS, MFT, Therapist in Miami, Florida. May be an image of text that says 'Yes, AND @HOLISTICALLYGRACE we can be grateful Yes, WISH THINGS WERE DIFFERENT AND we can love our family Yes, FEEL OVERWHELMED BY THEIR PRESENCE AND we can miss someone Yes, AND KNOW WE DESERVED MORE we can rest Yes, STILL BE PRODUCTIVE AND'.

node.text:
If you didn’t already know…AND is one of my favorite words. It gives us freedom, creates space for multiple emotions and realities. It shows the complexity of our human nature. ⠀

Yes, we can love our family dearly AND still need to set boundaries so we can conserve our energy. No, this does not mean we are "bad." Yes, we really need to get off the gerbil wheel, give ourselves the rest we deserve AND no, this does not make us lazy. After relationships end we can miss someone, the comfort they provided AND know they were really toxic to our wellbeing. Yes, we can happy AND sad AND no, that is not a contradiction.⠀

We were not meant for the box created by the either/or world, we were meant for the freedom of AND. ⠀

How would you fill out your own YES, AND? What are some things you are struggling to consolidate? How can we give ourselves the permission to hold space for it all?

May be an image of text that says '"I don't know enough about this subject, ー can refer you to someone who does" "I don't know and I may never get the answers I want" Normalize not @holisticallygrace knowing: "I don't know, we have to give it some time, space to see how it unfolds" "I don't know, let me get back to you" "I don't know but I'm holding myself accountkable and learning"'.

node.text:
All that I know is that I don’t know.

Not knowing triggers two things: a discomfort of the mind/body system in the form of stress (due to lack of information and uncertainty) usually followed by narrative that we’re incompetent.

Create space in your life for not knowing. Practice saying “I don’t know” lean into it and know that it’s not attached to your worth. It just means you don’t know...yet.

Do you feel uncomfortable saying I don’t know?

Note: this does not apply to situations where it IS your job to know and failure to do so may result in harm/consequences for others-this is negligence.

Also: normalize typos 🤦‍♀️🤷🏼‍♀️

node.text:
Sometimes, you just have to sit in the suck. Sorry, no helpful or colorful info-graphic for this one!

Also, if that last one doesn’t feel authentic or realistic at the moment, leave it. Take only what you need.

I just happen to think there’s space for hope, even in the dark and twisty. 

Also, also, yes, I know this a “list” post about there not being a list for this kinda thing 🤷🏼‍♀️

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Maria Sosa, MS, MFT, Therapist in Miami, Florida. May be an image of text that says 'OFTEN, WHAT HURTS MOST ABOUT OTHER'S ACTIONS... is the meaning we attach to them Not being invited to social gathering don't belong, am not likable" Getting ghosted, broken up with, told they're not looking for anything serious "I wasn't chosen, am not lovable" Having mistakes, flaws pointed out "I'm incompetent, am worthless" Distancing by family, friends, loved ones "I'm too much, I'm not enough" @holisticallygrace'.

node.text:
Do other’s actions hurt us? Yes. Do we add an extra layer once we attach meaning to those actions? Also yes.

While our natural tendency is to attach meaning and try to understand the “why” behind others actions (as it relates to our inadequacies, flaws, lack of worth, etc.)-the reality is we can separate the two. 

We can look at the behaviors, let others know how their actions are hurting us, look for ways to cope, repair AND re-story the reasons behind their actions in a way that doesn’t attack our innate worth.

What are some meanings you have attached to other’s actions? My favorite go-to is the “I’m not likable” - every single time 😫

If you'd like to talk about what's bothering you, I'm listening. •I didn't like that, it wasn't funny to me. Please stop. •I understand it feels unfair and to honor this boundary. need .I'd rather remove myself from the situation. don't feel welcome or comfortable. •I don't want to discuss this anymore. I have nothing else to add.'.

node.text:
Often, saying what we feel and honoring our needs/boundaries feel “mean.” If we want to grow, we’re going to have to push past the discomfort of the label.

As always (and especially on social media) discernment is important. Are we using these to avoid conversations? Is our tone, body language confrontational or aggressive? Are we balancing and being flexible or is rigidity the norm? 

These are all worth incorporating into the layers.

What else would you add? Share below!

May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'BEFORE giving your opinion, solution or trying to 'fix it" ASK listen with empathy, share: sit with -are you looking for space, time to process? -do you just want to vent? -is it ok if you? -what do you need from me? -how can i best help right now? -are you asking for my opinion? -i hear you -that makes sense -that sounds tough -i don't know what to say and I'm here for you -it's ok (and helpful) if you want to cry -what you're feeling/ experiencing is valid THEN'.

node.text:
Often, in our attempt to help others, we go into fix-it mode; giving our opinions, sharing our experiences and solutions, seeking to take the other person’s pain away. 

The reality is that one of the best ways we can support our loved ones is to show them that they are heard, seen, and understood. Most of the time, we don’t even need to say anything at all, just sit, hold space, and listen.

How do you like to be shown support?

P.s. If what you are looking for IS solutions and problem-solving, by all means, ask for that!

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Maria Sosa, MS, MFT, Therapist in Miami, Florida. May be a cartoon of text that says 'feeling that you can share, be vulnerable, without being judged validation of other's perspective, emotions even if we don't agree accountability, apologizing for hurtful behaviors, repairing emotional safety in a relationship @holisticallygrace looks like: physiological ease, not feeling flooded, anxious in their presence tackling of difficult conversations, mutual trust, best interest at heart acceptance of boundaries, without punishment, retribution'.

node.text:
Before we can experience connection, we need to feel safe.

Safety in relationships are not a given. It builds through time, interactions, trial and error, taking risks and learning when we hurt/hurt others.

A first for emotional safety: not rushing. You don’t have to share your most vulnerable moments to create connection. Start small, dip your toes, give yourself time to enjoy the build up.

How do you know when you are emotionally safe?

The discomfort feel doesn't make it a mistake. 2 The choice may disappoint' others and it is the one need to feel ease and peace. 3 This is the choice am making right now. free change my mind, reevaluate, and choose again. am The choice I made hono ed the knowing and wisdom within. Even if it went against the "shoulds" and logic/rationale. ハ'.

node.text:
Currently: not thinking in binary terms.

Our brains like simplicity and certainty. “Right/wrong”- “Good/bad.” 

And while it may like to categorize and label, the reality is that complexity rules. There are tonalities, hues, contexts, circumstances.

One of the areas where we often get stuck is decision-making and trying to pin the tail on the “right” or “wrong” donkey.

To get ourselves unstuck, we can:  Expand and add more layers, Understand that even the “right” choices make us feel pain, Notice that we can’t truly know everything and that time and space will provide information.

Please share below some new ways of expanding beyond the “right/wrong” duality!

Note: This does not apply to abuse or harm caused to others. This is never ok.

May be an image of text that says 'Mental Health Stigma OFTEN MEANS: Dismissiveness, invalidation from family, friends: "It's all in your head, try harder" Debilitating shame, negative feelings about self: "I'm broken, worthless" Isolation: "No one really gets what I'm going through Harassment, social re jection: "They're, crazy" Diminished quality of life: I'm fine, don't need help" @HOLISTICALLYGRACEX @PBS'.

node.text:
In case we missed the memo, we all experienced a collective traumatic experience over the last year. In one way or another, it made us realize the importance and delicateness of our mental health. And while that often invalidated component of our health has come to the forefront of our attention, so has the stigma. 

There are still many unknowns about the functioning of our brain but the data on mental health stigma is very clear: it has serious and devastating effects for us all, as individuals and as a society.

If you didn't already know...I'm a lover of science and nerdy documentaries. My newest addition and love? @pbs ‘s "Mysteries of Mental Illness"- a four-hour documentary series exploring the story of mental illness in science and society. There were so many mind blowing and ah-ha moments! If you haven't already checked it out, I highly recommend it.

Stream it now on the @pbs Video App!
